. Messner probes the richly complex gender dynamics of youth sports. Weaving together vivid first-person interviews with his own experiences as a volunteer for his sons' teams, Messner finds that despite the movement of girls into sports, gender boundaries and hierarchies still dominate, especially among the adults who run youth sports. His book widens into a provocative exploration of why youth sports matter—how they play a profound role in shaping gender, class, family, and community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aParent and child. 0aSports for childrenxCoaching. 0aSports for childrenxPsychological aspects. 0aSports for children. 0aSportsxSex differences. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh  aamerican culture.  aamerican sports.  abaseball.  aclass distinction.  acultural studies.  ademographic studies.  adiversity.  afamily.  afirst person interviews.  agender and childhood.  agender boundaries.  agender difference.  agender dynamics.  agender equality.  agender hierarchies.  agender norms.  agender studies.  agender.  alittle leagues.  aparent organized youth sports.  aparents and children.  aparents.  aracial inequality.  asoccer.  asociology.  asoftball.  asport sociology.  asports.  ateam sports.  ayouth sports.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025710840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094345240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943452/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY